Pour the @water{400%ml} into a large #saucepan{}, bring to the boil, then stir in the
@chicken stock powder{1/2}. When the water is boiling and the stock pot has dissolved,
reduce the heat to low so the stock keeps hot.

In the meantime, halve, peel and thinly slice the @echalion shallot{1} into half moons.
Roughly chop the @chestnut mushrooms{150%g}. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use
a #garlic press{}). Finely chop the @chives{1} (or snip with #scissors{} if you have some).

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in another large saucepan over medium heat. When hot, add the
@diced chicken thigh{140%g} and cook until nicely browned all over, stirring frequently,
~{5%minutes}. Add the shallot, mushrooms and @dried thyme{1/2%tsp}. Stir and cook for
another ~{5%minutes}.

> TIP: If you have a spare glass of white wine, add it now and allow it to bubble away.

Stir in the garlic and @orzo{180%g}. Cook for ~{1%minute} more, then add a third of the
hot stock. Bring to the boil and give it a good stir. Lower the heat until the orzotto is
gently bubbling away, then pour in the remaining stock.

Simmer the orzotto for ~{10-12%minutes}, stirring every now and then to make sure it is
not catching on the bottom of the pan.

> TIP: The orzotto is ready when the stock has been absorbed and the grains have a little
> bite to them.
> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle.

Remove the orzotto from the heat when it is ready and stir in the chives,
@mature cheddar cheese{60%g}(grated) and a little squeeze of @lemon{1/2}(juiced). Taste and
add @salt{} , @pepper{} or more lemon juice to taste. Dress the @wild rocket{40%g} with a
squeeze of lemon juice and a glug of @oil{}. Spoon the orzotto into deep #bowls{} and
serve with the rocket on top. Enjoy!